import{_ as a,c as t,o as i,aA as n}from"./chunks/framework.CLrzXryn.js";const o="/RadialBasisFunctions.jl/previews/PR125/assets/p_refinement_interpolation.BtBWL3S2.png",s="/RadialBasisFunctions.jl/previews/PR125/assets/p_refinement_laplacian.HhHH_JKx.png",r="/RadialBasisFunctions.jl/previews/PR125/assets/p_refinement_gradient.O6FsahZB.png",l="/RadialBasisFunctions.jl/previews/PR125/assets/p_refinement_cost.CpcO9dZ7.png",p="/RadialBasisFunctions.jl/previews/PR125/assets/k_refinement_laplacian.BApi9ohn.png",c="/RadialBasisFunctions.jl/previews/PR125/assets/k_refinement_gradient.Com_vOaq.png",d="/RadialBasisFunctions.jl/previews/PR125/assets/eps_refinement_imq.YGs5Wm_z.png",h="/RadialBasisFunctions.jl/previews/PR125/assets/eps_refinement_gaussian.BvKtGz4c.png",m="/RadialBasisFunctions.jl/previews/PR125/assets/eps_polydeg_sweep_imq.D6lY85Tf.png",u="/RadialBasisFunctions.jl/previews/PR125/assets/eps_polydeg_sweep_gaussian.BVF9fXtL.png",k=JSON.parse('{"title":"Refinement Sweeps","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"guides/convergence/refinement-sweeps.md","filePath":"guides/convergence/refinement-sweeps.md","lastUpdated":null}'),f={name:"guides/convergence/refinement-sweeps.md"};function g(y,e,_,b,v,w){return i(),t("div",null,[...e[0]||(e[0]=[n('<h1 id="Refinement-Sweeps" tabindex="-1">Refinement Sweeps <a class="header-anchor" href="#Refinement-Sweeps" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Refinement Sweeps {#Refinement-Sweeps}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h1><p>Three refinement knobs act orthogonally to the point count <code>N</code>:</p><ul><li><p><strong>p-refinement</strong>: polynomial augmentation degree at fixed <code>N</code></p></li><li><p><strong>k-refinement</strong>: stencil size (nearest neighbors per point) at fixed <code>N</code>, <code>poly_deg</code></p></li><li><p><strong>Œµ-refinement</strong>: shape parameter for <code>IMQ</code> / <code>Gaussian</code></p></li></ul><h2 id="Polynomial-degree-p-refinement" tabindex="-1">Polynomial degree (p-refinement) <a class="header-anchor" href="#Polynomial-degree-p-refinement" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Polynomial degree (p-refinement) {#Polynomial-degree-p-refinement}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h2><p>With all other parameters fixed, error typically decreases with each increment of <code>poly_deg</code> until the basis smoothness caps the achievable rate. Beyond that point, additional polynomial degree adds cost (more monomials, larger local systems) with no accuracy benefit.</p><h3 id="Interpolation" tabindex="-1">Interpolation <a class="header-anchor" href="#Interpolation" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Interpolation {#Interpolation}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><img src="'+o+'" alt=""></p><p>Each curve is flat ‚Äî polynomial degree has essentially no effect on <code>Interpolator</code> accuracy at fixed <code>N</code>. This is not a bug. <code>Interpolator</code> is a <strong>global</strong> method: it uses all <code>N</code> points in one collocation system, so the RBF&#39;s native smoothness already reproduces the target to whatever accuracy that kernel can achieve, and the polynomial augmentation contributes only a low-order reproducing property that doesn&#39;t change the answer on a smooth non-polynomial target like Franke. Contrast with the local-stencil differential operators below, where <code>poly_deg</code> controls local approximation and matters a great deal.</p><p><strong>Practical implication:</strong> for <code>Interpolator</code>, pick the smallest <code>poly_deg</code> that meets your reproducing-polynomial needs (usually <code>poly_deg = 2</code>) ‚Äî going higher adds cost without accuracy.</p><h3 id="Laplacian" tabindex="-1">Laplacian <a class="header-anchor" href="#Laplacian" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Laplacian {#Laplacian}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><img src="'+s+'" alt=""></p><p>IMQ and Gaussian hit a stagnation floor around <code>poly_deg=3‚Äì4</code> for this problem size ‚Äî the shape parameter becomes the bottleneck. PHS curves keep dropping.</p><h3 id="Gradient" tabindex="-1">Gradient <a class="header-anchor" href="#Gradient" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Gradient {#Gradient}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><img src="'+r+'" alt=""></p><h3 id="Cost-side" tabindex="-1">Cost side <a class="header-anchor" href="#Cost-side" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Cost side {#Cost-side}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><img src="'+l+'" alt=""></p><p>Higher <code>poly_deg</code> grows the local system size as <code>binomial(d+p, p)</code> in <code>d</code> dimensions ‚Äî in 2D that&#39;s 1, 3, 6, 10, 15, 21 monomials for <code>p = 0..5</code>. Build time grows super-linearly.</p><h2 id="Stencil-size-k-refinement" tabindex="-1">Stencil size (k-refinement) <a class="header-anchor" href="#Stencil-size-k-refinement" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Stencil size (k-refinement) {#Stencil-size-k-refinement}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h2><p>The number of nearest neighbors per stencil. <code>autoselect_k(data, basis)</code> picks a reasonable default based on the basis order.</p><h3 id="Interpolation-2" tabindex="-1">Interpolation <a class="header-anchor" href="#Interpolation-2" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Interpolation {#Interpolation-2}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><code>Interpolator</code> uses a <em>global</em> stencil (all points), so k-refinement does not apply.</p><h3 id="Laplacian-2" tabindex="-1">Laplacian <a class="header-anchor" href="#Laplacian-2" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Laplacian {#Laplacian-2}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><img src="'+p+'" alt=""></p><p>A clear U-shape: too few neighbors under-resolves the local polynomial; too many introduces extraneous points that hurt local fit quality. For PHS5/p=3 the sweet spot is around k=15‚Äì20; PHS7/p=4 minimizes around k=20‚Äì25. The exact optimum depends on point distribution, so the autoselect defaults give a safe starting point rather than a tuned one.</p><h3 id="Gradient-2" tabindex="-1">Gradient <a class="header-anchor" href="#Gradient-2" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Gradient {#Gradient-2}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><img src="'+c+'" alt=""></p><p>Same U-shape with minima at similar k. First-derivative operators are less sensitive to stencil size than second-derivative ones.</p><h2 id="Shape-parameter-Œµ-refinement" tabindex="-1">Shape parameter (Œµ-refinement) <a class="header-anchor" href="#Shape-parameter-Œµ-refinement" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Shape parameter (Œµ-refinement) {#Shape-parameter-Œµ-refinement}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h2><p>IMQ and Gaussian use a shape parameter <code>Œµ</code> that controls basis width. Smaller <code>Œµ</code> yields flatter (wider-support) basis functions ‚Äî in principle more accurate, but the corresponding linear systems become severely ill-conditioned, so numerical error dominates below a threshold.</p><h3 id="IMQ-shape-parameter-sensitivity" tabindex="-1">IMQ shape-parameter sensitivity <a class="header-anchor" href="#IMQ-shape-parameter-sensitivity" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;IMQ shape-parameter sensitivity {#IMQ-shape-parameter-sensitivity}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><img src="'+d+'" alt=""></p><p>Interpolation has a sharp minimum around <code>Œµ ‚âà 3</code>, with error 100√ó worse at Œµ=0.1 or Œµ=10. Differential operators have gentler U-curves with optima around <code>Œµ ‚âà 0.3‚Äì0.5</code>.</p><h3 id="Gaussian-shape-parameter-sensitivity" tabindex="-1">Gaussian shape-parameter sensitivity <a class="header-anchor" href="#Gaussian-shape-parameter-sensitivity" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Gaussian shape-parameter sensitivity {#Gaussian-shape-parameter-sensitivity}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><img src="'+h+'" alt=""></p><h3 id="Effect-of-poly_deg-on-Œµ-sensitivity-IMQ-Laplacian" tabindex="-1">Effect of poly_deg on Œµ sensitivity (IMQ Laplacian) <a class="header-anchor" href="#Effect-of-poly_deg-on-Œµ-sensitivity-IMQ-Laplacian" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Effect of poly_deg on Œµ sensitivity (IMQ Laplacian) {#Effect-of-poly_deg-on-Œµ-sensitivity-IMQ-Laplacian}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><img src="'+m+'" alt=""></p><p>Higher polynomial augmentation flattens the Œµ dependence ‚Äî the polynomial basis absorbs the responsibility for low-frequency modes, making the system less reliant on tuning <code>Œµ</code> precisely.</p><h3 id="Effect-of-poly_deg-on-Œµ-sensitivity-Gaussian-Laplacian" tabindex="-1">Effect of poly_deg on Œµ sensitivity (Gaussian Laplacian) <a class="header-anchor" href="#Effect-of-poly_deg-on-Œµ-sensitivity-Gaussian-Laplacian" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Effect of poly_deg on Œµ sensitivity (Gaussian Laplacian) {#Effect-of-poly_deg-on-Œµ-sensitivity-Gaussian-Laplacian}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><p><img src="'+u+'" alt=""></p><h3 id="Practical-guidance" tabindex="-1">Practical guidance <a class="header-anchor" href="#Practical-guidance" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Practical guidance {#Practical-guidance}&quot;">‚Äã</a></h3><ul><li><p>For routine use, start at <code>Œµ = 1.0</code> with <code>poly_deg = 2</code> ‚Äî it&#39;s within a factor of 10 of optimal for every operator in the sweeps above.</p></li><li><p>Only tune <code>Œµ</code> if you&#39;re chasing the last order of magnitude and have benchmark data from your specific problem geometry.</p></li><li><p>For ill-conditioning concerns, use PHS ‚Äî it has no shape parameter and doesn&#39;t exhibit the &quot;flatter is better until it isn&#39;t&quot; tradeoff.</p></li></ul>',41)])])}const q=a(f,[["render",g]]);export{k as __pageData,q as default};
